{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778768255,"nonce":"h+ESsHtR/dTlnzElQGLj/FblbWQ=","message":"The `35f64be` implementation plan ends the experimental flow at Phase 4 (cs_faithful GRU arm). But the eventual interpretability target needs to be on a delayed-reach version (with hold + target_on + movement epochs, production plant), because that's what the b399efc work has calibrated and what's directly comparable to human paradigms. The gate doesn't propagate to that target as a *gate* — it propagates as a *certified training pipeline plus a set of cs_faithful reference signatures*. Bridging is a chain of separate experiments, each adding one complication, with cs_faithful results as the consistency anchor at each step.\n\n\n| Stage | Plant | Task structure | Adversary scope | Analytical anchor | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Gate (per Codex) | cs_faithful (k=0.1, τ=0.066) | hold-free, single canonical reach | full-state ε over whole rollout | cs_faithful Riccati | Certify the training pipeline solves the H∞ game |\n| Bridge 1: plant | production (k=10, τ=0.05) | hold-free, single canonical reach | full-state ε over whole rollout | new Riccati at production plant | Verify pipeline still solves the H∞ game when plant params shift |\n| Bridge 2: targets | production | hold-free, **center-out 8-direction** | full-state ε, per-trial | cs_faithful Riccati per-direction (if tractable) | Verify generalisation across reach directions |\n| Bridge 3: delayed-reach | production | hold + target_on + movement epochs | ε **only in movement epoch** | cs_faithful Riccati on movement epoch only | Add preparation/hold structure; check movement-epoch signatures match Bridge 2 |\n| Interpretability | production | delayed-reach | as above | (none direct) | Dynamical-systems analysis on Bridge 3 GRU |\n\n\n- **Each bridge is a consistency check, not a fresh gate.** At each step, the GRU's movement-epoch signatures (Δv, gain modulation, induced gain, K_local profile on standardised perturbations) should match the prior step's signatures within tolerance. If they do, the learned solution persists across the added complication. If they don't, that's a substantive finding about which task feature changes the solution.\n\n- **ε adversary must be epoch-gated in Bridge 3.** Active only during the movement epoch; hold/target_on left clean. Implementation requires the intervenor to honour `epoch_mask(\"movement\")` from the task's `TrialTimeline`. Without this, the adversary perturbs preparation state too — a different (probably ill-defined analytically) game.\n\n- **Asymmetric anchoring**. The gate certifies the *movement-epoch H∞ behaviour*; the hold-period dynamics are anchored only to b399efc's empirical baseline (movement_ramp schedule, prego penalties), not to any analytical target. Both are interesting; they're interpreted against different references.\n\n- **Stage-1 plant bridge is non-trivial**. cs_faithful's k=0.1 vs production's k=10 (per decision record `a04711e`) is a 100× damping change. The pipeline-pass certification at cs_faithful does NOT automatically extend to production plant; that bridge step needs its own Riccati re-derivation and consistency check. Codex's critique resolved this by deferring production training entirely until cs_faithful passes — Stage 1 in the table above is what comes after.\n\n- **Bridge 2 may be hard analytically**. cs2019's Riccati for a single canonical reach is well-defined; extending to center-out generalises naturally for an LTI plant with rotational symmetry, but the worst-case ε per-direction may differ from a single shared ε across directions. Codex's \"single canonical reach for the gate, not mixed targets\" applies specifically to the gate; once gate passes, Bridge 2 is where mixed-direction analysis enters.\n\n\nWhen `35f64be` gets revised after Codex's critique, this bridging chain should appear as an explicit \"What comes after Phase 4\" section — currently the plan stops at Phase 4 with a vague \"next steps\" pointer to `0c95d6b`. The fuller picture is: Phase 4 produces the cs_faithful GRU; Stages 1-3 of the chain above are separate follow-up experiments that establish whether the cs_faithful signature persists under plant changes, target variety, and task structure complications; only Stage 4 (interpretability) is where `0c95d6b` and the affine-decomposition work actually live.\n\nFolding this into the revised plan also clarifies why **two of the OPEN questions** from the original plan are properly resolved by being deferred to Bridge stages, not by being answered now:\n- Q1 (production plant): not Phase 1b of `35f64be`; it's Bridge 1 of this chain — a separate experiment after the gate.\n- Q4 (delayed-reach hold/catch): not Phase 4 of `35f64be`; it's Bridge 3 of this chain.\n\nThis isn't an alternative to Codex's framing — it's compatible. Codex said \"cs_faithful first, production as bridge later, decision tree for outcomes a/b/c,\" and this comment articulates *what \"production as bridge later\" actually means as a sequence*.","files":null}]}